to the editor in proposed rule would ease stance on feeding at nursing homes news article sept 25 you suggest that nursing home residents will somehow be placed at risk if nursing homes are allowed to hire and train feeding assistants to help out at meal times in fact this new regulation will permit nursing homes to serve their residents better and with more personal attention at the busiest times of day the new rule includes ample safeguards for resident safety and can also free nurses and nursing assistants to focus on the more complex feeding and caregiving tasks nursing homes that have tested the use of feeding assistants typically train and include their non nursing staff too so that at busy meal times it 's all hands on deck to help residents too frail to feed themselves the objective is a better quality of life for those in their care william l minnix jr president american association of homes and services for the aging washington sept 29 2003

